#[doc("""
stdlib/fs/path.kai — re-export shim for the existing `path_*`
helpers from `stdlib/path.kai`.

Module path: `import fs.path`. Catalog: `docs/stdlib-layout.md`
§`fs`. Roadmap: `docs/stdlib-roadmap.md` Tier S1 #1.

v1 STATUS: doc-only stub. The `path_*` helpers (`path_join`,
`path_dirname`, `path_basename`, `path_ext`, `path_strip_ext`,
`path_split`, `path_is_absolute`) live in `stdlib/path.kai`,
which the `bin/kai` driver auto-loads as a prelude — so every
program already has them as globally-visible flat names. The
qualified-call resolver (`me_lookup_export`,
stage2/compiler.kai) additionally rewrites `path.join(a, b)` to
the flat `path_join(a, b)` because `path` is a registered module
entry. Both surfaces work today without any code in this file.

What this file does NOT yet do is forward the same surface under
the `fs.path.*` name. m6.2 has no `pub use foo` re-export
mechanism — a re-export shim would have to either (a) import the
original module and define new `pub fn` thunks (`pub fn fs_path_join(a, b) =
path_join(a, b)`), doubling the surface for zero new behaviour,
or (b) wait for the m14 module-system rename lane to teach the
resolver about transitive aliases. Option (a) is intentionally
deferred — `fs.path.*` is the catalog name, not a different API
than `path.*`, and shipping a thunk layer just to reify the
nesting is exactly the "duplicate intent" CLAUDE.md warns
against. Option (b) is the real fix.

Until the m14 rename lane runs, callers wanting the `fs/`
namespace should write `path.join(a, b)` (qualified) or
`path_join(a, b)` (flat). Both work and resolve to the same
implementation.

Follow-up tracking: `docs/stdlib-roadmap.md` Tier S1 #1 closing
PR will note the deferred re-export under the issue label
`stdlib` once the m14 module rename lane opens.
""")]
